SERRATIA MARCESCENS - AUSTRALIA: (SOUTH AUSTRALIA) NEONATAL UNIT
*****************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Thu 4 Jun 2020
Source: ABC News [edited]
https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-06-04/three-more-babies-test-positive-for-rare-bacteria-at-flinders/12319332


Three more babies at an Adelaide [the capital city of the state of South Australia (SA), Australia] hospital have tested positive for a rare bacterium, after health authorities yesterday [Wed 3 Jun 2020] confirmed 5 had been infected.

Southern Adelaide Local Health Network medical services director Diana Lawrence said the latest cases at Flinders Medical Centre had tested positive for the bacteria _Serratia marcescens_ but had "no symptoms of infection" [that is, these patients were colonized, not infected].

The outbreak has been linked to a basin, and the bacteria can cause meningitis and other conditions including urinary and respiratory infections.

"Three additional babies have now been confirmed as colonised with _Serratia_ but have no symptoms of infection," Dr Lawrence said in a statement. "An active investigation is underway to determine any links between the confirmed cases and babies colonised and the hand basin."

SA Health yesterday [Wed 3 Jun 2020] revealed one baby at the southern suburbs hospital was in a serious but stable condition after becoming infected with the bacteria. Another of the infants is showing symptoms, and 3 more had tested positive but were showing no symptoms, SA Health said. Dr Lawrence said antibiotics would be administered "only on a case-by-case basis, dependent on clinical need."

The bacterium was 1st detected in the unit 2 weeks ago, but the outbreak was not publicly revealed until yesterday [Wed 3 Jun 2020]. The hospital is carrying out an investigation into how the bacteria entered the neonatal unit.

One of 200 environmental swabs taken of the unit, from a hand-washing basin, came back positive for the bacteria. The basin has since been removed and replaced.

Australian Medical Association state president Chris Moy said the hospital was "unlucky" to have had an outbreak. "This hospital's got the highest rating on handwashing that you can get; it's also the one with the least number of serious infections in Australia," Dr Moy said.

Dr Lawrence said closing the area where the bacteria was found left the capacity of the hospital "slightly reduced" but said expectant parents should not change their plans. "While we're diverting some to the Women's and Children's, and we can't divert them all, we've only closed 4 out of 16 neonatal beds," she said. "We're very much open for business; we've just decreased our activity somewhat."

[Byline: Leah MacLennan]

